(Eng)

In the Hong Kong (HK) Smart City Blueprint, smart mobility is one of the main initiatives outlined by the Government. “Bicycle-friendly” new towns are explicitly addressed in the blueprint for their strategic importance in enhancing the mobility of the city.

 

The key to effective cycle facility planning is the understanding of the cycling activities. Different from motor vehicle roads, the information about the usage of cycle tracks and bicycle flows is typically not known to the governments, municipalities, or relevant authorities. This issue is a problem not only in HK, but also in other countries and cities. Traditional and widely adopted data collection methods include surveys and manual counts. However, these methods may have large estimation errors due to the sampling scheme or human mistakes. Also, they are not cost-efficient because of the high manpower costs. Motivated by the advance in technologies, we will develop a smart, novel, reliable, and automated system for cycling demand estimation. 

This project aims to develop a comprehensive smart bike traffic estimation solution, powered by a set of advanced technologies and engineering methods, including sensing technologies (thermography cameras), computer vision, data-driven algorithms, and traffic engineering techniques.

The novelty of the proposed project is threefold. 

1. From an application point of view, this project delivers an innovative framework that captures information about cycling activities automatically and continuously. The data collected in this study can facilitate new research on cycle infrastructure planning and cycling safety.

2. From a technological aspect, multiple advanced technologies are deployed for performance cross-validation and enhancement. The use of thermography cameras can address privacy concerns.

3. From a methodological aspect, a cost-effective flow estimation method which deploys both permanent and mobile thermal imaging cameras for flow estimation is proposed. State-of-the-art machine learning and artificial intelligence algorithms are integrated for bike flow estimation and insight discovery. 

To demonstrate the practicality of the proposed approach, a pilot study will be conducted in the network of the cycle tracks in Hong Kong Science and Technology Park (HKSTP). Nevertheless, the R&D outcomes can be generalized to other cycle and vehicular infrastructures in HK and other parts of the world.

This project is expected to

  • enhance convenience of cyclists through better planning of cycle network;
  • enhance efficiency of the cycle tracks and space;
  • provide useful datasets on and non-trivial insights into cycling accidents and safety; and
  • promote smart mobility and sustainable transportation in HK.

In the Hong Kong Smart City Blueprint, smart mobility is one of the main initiatives outlined by the Government. “Bicycle-friendly” new towns are explicitly addressed in the blueprint for their strategic importance in enhancing the mobility of the city. Hong Kong is the fourth-most densely populated region in the world and has over 90% of daily journeys made by public transit. Technical Background

Despite the improved cycling facilities in urban environments, little effort has been spent developing comprehensive surveillance systems for bicycle traffic flow. To better understand the underlying mobility patterns of cyclists in the urban areas, specifically, to estimate the bicycle kilometrage (BKM), a novel, efficient and real-time framework for bicycle traffic monitoring will be proposed. With the information about bicycle kilometrages in different towns and regions, Government units would be able to have a better planning of the cycle facilities. Bicycle speeds and bike flows would also be estimated at different locations to understand the riders’ behaviors. Once we collect the data, we will utilize ideas from the annual trafﬁc census (ATC) to conduct statistical analysis, and the result will be validated by ground truth.

Data Collection

Detection Technology

This is a computer vision-based system, where thermal cameras are deployed at bike lane intersections. The system is capable of reliably detecting, classifying, and tracking cyclists and other road users and objects. Moreover, this method will be robust to deal with various complex traffic scenes and types of environmental conditions.

Sensor System

Implementing a detection system requires careful considerations. Traditional transportation surveillance systems heavily rely on intrusive detectors, of which the installation might damage the roads and impede the traffic. Loop detectors are one of the most common intrusive devices. They are buried underneath the roads to detect the presence of vehicles, which is considerably expensive in installation. Moreover, their measurements provide little information for road user classification among cars, bicycles, and pedestrians (Bahler et al., 1998). These deficiencies and limitations in data collection can hamper the efforts to encourage and improve bicycle travel. Recently, non-intrusive detectors have been enjoying growing popularity. Especially with the advancements in computer vision technologies, video-based techniques have been extensively researched and applied for more accurate and secure monitoring systems.

Vision-based methods mainly utilize passive cameras at low cost, fixed at intersections to capture traffic information and produce real-time video streams for further analysis. There are primarily two types of these digital video-based cameras (visible or thermal). Figure 1 shows a vision-based traffic detector developed by SIEMENS. An Visible spectrum cameras, also referred to as RGB cameras, rely on the visible light spectrum to produce high-resolution videos, which contain rich context for colors, textures, edges, and other information with little noise (Gerónimo et al., 2010). Such visual sensors have been widely deployed for traffic sign detection and lane detection (Li et al., 2016). However, these detectors are limited by their sensitivity to environmental factors, such as lighting, shadow, and extreme weather (Fu et al., 2015; Yoneyama et al., 2005). For example, during the daytime, shadows and glare may impair the accuracy of extracted videos. During the nighttime, the illumination and blurriness can also challenge the performance of detection and tracking. Therefore, developing a vision-based traffic sensor that can work under all types of ambient conditions becomes a pressing issue.

Figure 1. Vision-based traffic detector developed by SIEMENS

Figure 2. A thermal image that captures road traffic

Recently, new camera technologies have driven the applications of thermal imaging cameras in traffic surveillance, an alternative to overcome the shortcomings of visible cameras. Figure 2 illustrates a thermal image that captures road traffic. Thermal cameras capture the long-wavelength infrared radiation emitted from all objects with a temperature above absolute zero. In thermal video data, objects are visualized through the temperature difference from the surroundings (Gade & Moeslund, 2014). Thus, its operation does not need the aid of an external light source, making it possible for “around the clock” data collection (Iwasaki et al., 2012). Insensitive to pavement temperature, thermal cameras are remarkably accurate to detect cyclists, our primary research objects, from other vehicles since the bikers’ bodies are better visible through thermal imaging (Collaert, 2013; Fu et al., 2016). Other objects on the ground are typically of lower temperatures, such that they may not affect the detection of the focused objects of our study (e.g., cyclists and pedestrians).      Furthermore, the focused objects are moving objects, as compared to other static objects, would be easily distinguished when comparing consecutive images of a video. While producing reliable and stable results, grayscale thermal videos have lower requirements in resolution, storage space, and computation resources (Fu et al., 2015). Also, they would not raise concerns regarding privacy issues. Recognizing these benefits, we will integrate thermal detectors for automatic traffic data collection. Although computer vision techniques and safety analysis have been intensively developed and tested on regular RGB videos, few studies have directly applied these methods to thermal imagery, especially involving cyclists. We will further evaluate the robustness of thermal videos used for cyclist detection.

Detection Phase

Traditional human detection would follow a typical pipeline, which consists of (a) sensor system, (b) region of proposals, (c) feature extraction, and (d) classification (Brunetti, Buongiorno, Trotta, & Bevilacqua, 2018). This pipeline relies on manual labelling and machine learning techniques, such as Histogram of Oriented Gradients (HOG) for feature extraction and Support Vector Machine (SVM) as the classifier (Dalal et al., 2005). However, with the advent of deep learning, a subset of Artificial Intelligence, the performance and effectiveness of vision-based object detection have been significantly improved. Thus, traditional detection methods based on simple machine learning get obsolete. In the progress of deep learning techniques, Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) are particularly powerful to digest image data and deal with complex scenarios (Krizhevsky et al., 2012). So, the deep network-based approach, typically a CNN-based approach, has become the “cornerstone” for object recognition and classification, having great potential for accurate cyclist detection (Tomè et al., 2016).

Before introducing CNN, it is difficult for basic neural networks to extract features directly from the raw pixels of images efficiently. However, CNN can tackle this challenge by learning condensed vector representations of input data, with each layer using a filter. Information about the color of each pixel in an image will be extracted, and the pixels are organized in a vector format in an order of their positions. The vectors would be used as input for training to learn the patterns of particular objects for classification. A typical feed-forward neural network consists of an input layer, hidden layers, and an output layer. For CNN, its hidden layers include convolution layers, pooling layers, and fully connected layers interspersed with activation functions. Convolution layers would convolve (slide) over all the regions of the images to detect patterns and generate activation maps (Ordóñez & Roggen, 2016). Pooling layers would make the representations smaller and more manageable, considerably reducing the parameters to solve and lowering memory requirements. Fully connected layers contain neurons that connect to the entire input volumes, where matrices get flattened and ready for classification. When the layers go deeper, the representations of input data get more abstract, which is difficult for hand-crafted methods and introductory neural networks to achieve. These properties allow CNN to be standard practice to solve general object classification problems in the computer vision field, including cyclist detection. Figure 3 provides an overview of a CNN architecture.

Figure 3: Overview of a CNN architecture

Among the families of CNNs, there are mainly two categories of detectors: region proposal approach and non-region proposal approach. Region-based methods usually encompass two stages: a region proposal network, followed by a classification sub-network. The region proposal network uses selective search, which can give more than 2000 regions of interest (ROIs) in a few seconds on the CPU (Uijlings et al., 2013). Then the classification stage could make highly accurate predictions based on the proposed bounding boxes on the likely target objects, such as cyclists, pedestrians, or vehicles. Some works are inspired by this high-performance architecture, such as Region-CNN (R-CNN), Fast R-CNN, Faster R-CNN, and Regional-Fast Convolutional Network (R-FCN) (Dai et al., 2016; Girshick, 2015; Girshick et al., 2014; Ren et al., 2015). However, the second type detector, the non-region proposal approach, integrates region proposal and classification into a single network, which substantially improves computation efficiency (Ren, et al., 2017). Single Shot Detector (SSD) and You Only Look Once (YOLO) are typical examples of single-stage detectors (Hou et al., 2018; Liu et al., 2016; Redmon et al., 2016). In particular, YOLO’s detection pipeline is very high-speed, making it one of the most popular models for general-purpose object detection in a real-time manner. Real-time performance is essential to model bicycle traffic flow, and therefore, YOLO is our top candidate for the detection phase.

Information loss

Indicated by the name of YOLO, it makes the predictions by looking only once at the input data. YOLO considers object detection as a regression problem instead of assigning the class probabilities to the bounding boxes. The coordinates of boxes and class probabilities are predicted simultaneously in a single convolutional network (Redmon et al., 2016). So, it can efficiently break down the input image into representable portions. Although there may be slight trade-offs in detection accuracy, YOLO is still more competitive in real-time traffic detection tasks, nearly three times faster than region-based modules. Having been continuously iterated and improved, YOLO has four major versions: v1, v2, v3, and v4. The first version, YOLO v1, uses GoogleNet as a reference which is a deep Inception network. However, YOLO v1 simplifies inception modules into  convolutions, also called reduction layers, which can preserve spatial dimensions during convolutions and reduce the depth of the overall network (Redmon et al., 2016). Its successor, YOLO v2, significantly improved the performance and computation time by utilizing Darknet-19 as the backbone architecture and softmax classifier in the output layer (Redmon & Farhadi, 2017). Coming to YOLO v3, its backbone network is upgraded to Darknet-53, including residual blocks that can significantly boost deep networks' optimization performance. YOLO v3 made unprecedented progress in multi-label classification by using a logistic classifier (Redmon & Farhadi, 2018). Also, it can detect small objects, so that it works robustly even if the cyclists or other objects move to a tiny scale in the videos (Punn et al., 2020). The latest version, YOLO v4, further improved the computation speed and accuracy by designing a deeper and more complex network called Dense Block (Bochkovskiy et al., 2020). Overall, YOLO demonstrates strong generalization capabilities of processing multiple objects in video data.

Training a neural network to make accurate detection involves the optimization problem to a loss function. For YOLO, its loss function aggregates localization loss for bounding box regressor, confidence loss, and cross-entropy loss expressed as follows.

YOLO divides the frame into  grids, so there are  number of grids. For each grid cell, it predicts  bounding boxes, and each box has a confidence score. Tracking Phase

Once the cyclists or other road users have been detected upon their presence, the subsequent action tracks the given objects from frame to frame until they disappear from the image sequence. Inter-frame tracking is critical to reducing detection complexity. Otherwise, the detector might repeatedly identify the same moving objects yet regard them as different ones. However, tracking is challenging to deal with dynamic traffic scenes. For example, the appearance and pose of cyclists might frequently change, resulting in different orientations and aspect ratios. It is also likely that cyclists temporarily merge, split, or get occluded (Ahmed et al., 2019). To tackle these challenges, after carefully evaluating existing tracking methods, we would like to perform Deep SORT in the tracking phase, a deep learning-based approach to track multiple objects with effective algorithms (Wojke et al., 2017). Deep SORT has excellent potential to track individuals in surveillance systems, which is robust to handle occlusion and various viewpoints (Punn et al., 2020). This approach incorporates the Kalman filter and the Hungarian algorithm (Huang et al., 2008; Welch & Bishop, 1995).

Kalman filter is a widely applied technique in track handling and state estimation. It is reliably predictive of future states based on current conditions. This filtering framework defines the tracking scenario on the eight-dimensional state-space . The bounding box is described by  for the center position,  for aspect ratio, and  for height. The rest variables in  are their respective velocities in the image coordinates. Deep SORT uses standard Kalman filter, which means it considers constant velocity motion and linear observation model (Wojke & Bewley, 2018). The object state is directly expressed as the image coordinates (. For each track , the filter counts the number of frames starting from the latest successful measurement association . During the positive prediction of the filter, the counter is incremented. When the track is associated with measurement, it is reset to . Moreover, if a track exceeds a predefined maximum age , the filter will regard it to have disappeared from the scene and exclude it from the track set. New tracks will be initialized when a detection cannot be associated with any existing track. These new tracks are expected to have a successful association during the first three frames. Otherwise, they will get deleted after the first three frames.

The Hungarian algorithm can effectively solve mapping problems over the moving objects between the current and previous frames by assigning unique identifiers. Moreover, it combines two metrics to integrate appearance and motion information. The first one is the Mahalanobis distance between newly arrived measurements and Kalman's predicted positions, expressed as follows.

The Mahalanobis distance also considers the estimation uncertainty from the Kalman filter’s predicted states by calculating the standard deviations that the detection is away from the mean track location. Experiment

We will implement a pilot study at HKSTP for one year. The pilot study is expected to start in the 7th month of the project.

Camera Calibration

Camera calibration has a significant impact on detection accuracy. Thus, we will conduct camera calibration, which is expected to take two months. Traditionally, regular cameras for road surveillance are calibrated based on a pin-hole model, referring to the vanishing points from the traffic scenes. By solving a transformation matrix, it can project real-world positions of vehicles from the image planes. This model relies on road markings and standard calibration targets with known actual size. The primary purpose of such calibration is to measure the focal length, principal point, and lens distortion of a camera. However, thermal cameras are thermally calibrated without optical imaging based on temperature references to provide accurate thermal information. For most of the time, the cameras should have already been calibrated to factory specifications. In order to eliminate calibration shift and assure accurate temperature measurements, we still can go through the following steps for camera inspection and calibration:

  1. Perform a complete operational check throughout the camera system.
  2. Check that all the internal cable and Printed Circuit Board (PCB) connections can function normally.
  3. Upgrade the internal camera software to the latest version.
  4. Verify and re-equalize each temperature range for image uniformity if necessary. The thermal capability for a camera usually ranges from  to .
  5. Compute the ambient temperature compensation as needed. Since infrared radiation can be transmitted through or reflected from the objects, the ambient temperature can affect the measurement.

The thermal detectors are expected to be installed along with existing traffic equipment such as traffic lights, traffic signs, or street lights, to reduce the construction cost while being mounted at a certain height. In addition, these cameras should have a good view over the intersections, covering all the lanes. To achieve these goals, generally, the camera should look “down” the road for adequate visibility, illustrated by Figure 5. There is one parameter to determine during the setup: the tilt angle  downward from the horizontal line. To obtain a comprehensive vision, we will install two detectors at each point. Each detector will be parallel with the corresponding cycle path as shown in Figure 6. Considering the varying road conditions from intersection to intersection, we would like to follow a trial-and-error method to optimize the choices for these angles and maximize the detection performance. More specifically, during the experiment, we would collect several clips of short video footage by adjusting  from  to   at every -degree interval.

We will hire a professional contractor which has rich experience in installing cameras for similar projects in Hong Kong to manage all the installation and set-up issues in this pilot study. Cameras and sensors will be installed on the lampposts at the 18 locations in HKSTP, as shown in Figure 7. The installation cost has been budgeted in the proposal. The installation duration is expected to be 1 month, starting from the beginning of the project.

Proposed Methodology

ATC

ATC is a powerful system that measures the traffic volume using automatic traffic counters (Lam et al., 2003). In Hong Kong, there are over 1,500 counting stations divided into three groups: core (A), coverage (B), and coverage (C) stations. The main difference between the three types of stations is the data collection frequency, and the counting data at core stations are collected most frequently. Since the duration of measurement at coverage (B) and coverage (C) stations are not that long, a common way is grouping all stations into clusters and using scaling factors calculated from core stations to estimate traffic volumes at the coverage stations in each cluster. Moreover, typically 60% coverage (C) stations are unobserved and their traffic flows are predicted by the average growth factor of observed stations and measurements from previous years.

The road network in Hong Kong is classified as major networks and minor networks based on the importance of roads covered in each stratum. The number and allocation of counting stations in two classes of networks are quite different. For vehicle counts, there is a counting station at each link of Hong Kong’s major road network, while in the minor network stations are usually distributed next to cordons or screen-lines.

Classification of Counting Stations

As illustrated in Figure 7, a counting station is comprised of two detectors. In this pilot study the monitoring duration is only 12 months and thus non-sampled stations will not be required. In other words, we merely need two kinds of stations: core station with detailed measurement, and coverage station with short-duration measurement. Besides, there is one road type for bicycles and no stratification of cycle tracks is needed. Daily and hourly directional flows will be obtained at all stations, while the duration of measurement is one week per month at core stations, and only one week a year at coverage stations.

Number and Allocation of Detectors

In our plan, thermal detectors will be allocated at intersections and endpoints to recognize the option that the cyclist takes at the fork on roads, and following this idea we mark these locations and number them from (1) to (18) in Figure 7. Each of these locations will be allocated a counting station, either a core station or a coverage station.

Due to the resource constraints, we will treat 15% - 30% stations as core stations and others as coverage stations. Theoretically the core stations will be allocated randomly first, and the remaining locations will be assigned a coverage station. However, for a path segment with two stations at ends, we would not assign both stations be core with consideration of geographical information. The allocations of core stations are locations (2), (5), (9), (12) and (17), marked with a red star in Figure 7.

However, due to the power limit for coverage stations, we only install ten detectors fixedly at five core stations. This way can reduce the number of detectors we require. To collect data at coverage stations, we rely on the normal cameras. That is, we propose a “dual-camera” strategy: we will deploy video cameras at every point to obtain the ground truth data, which will be utilized to test the performance of the thermal camera system at core stations and provide data for coverage stations. The sampling strategies are listed in Table 3 below. To ensure the view is complete, two cameras will be required at each location. The video camera is parallel with the corresponding cycle path as shown in Figure 6 and only the tilt angle  should be found. Therefore, we will obtain the all-sided view for each intersection through 36 cameras. Since the video camera may not be sensitive at night or under extreme weather condition, the thermal detector might have a better performance. We can then compare their results to see whether they can cross-validate each other. The data fusion is potential as well.

For the links with core stations, the AADBT can be computed from bicycle counts directly (Tong et al., 2003). Accident Analysis

Exposure is indispensable in determining the incidence of bicycle crashes (Vanparijs et al., 2015). Once the bicycle exposure to accidents is available, we can develop the crash prediction model (Lord et al., 2021) to evaluate the safety performance of bicycle infrastructures based on the following steps.

Step 1: Extract bicycle crashes from the Traffic Road Accident Database during the study period. This database is maintained by the Hong Kong Police Force and the Hong Kong Transport Department. Despite the potential under-reporting of bicycle crashes, it is the solely representative data source throughout the Hong Kong territory and has been widely used for safety policymaking (Loo and Tsui, 2010; Xu et al., 2019).

Step 2: Geo-code bicycle crashes to the cycle tracks of interest given the available geographical coordinate information by virtue of the ArcGIS, and then validate the positioning accuracy by retrieving police narrative records.

Step 3: Partition the links into basic spatial units (BSU) based on homogeneity in geometric characteristics. In addition to the bicycle crashes and geometric characteristics, other built environment factors such as land use and greenness of each BSU can be collected by configuration of buffer zones with various sizes (e.g., 100m, 200m, and 400m). Digital land-use data can be readily obtained from the Hong Kong Planning Department, while eye-level greenness can be automatically extracted from the images captured by the Google Street View (Lu et al., 2019).

Step 4: Develop the crash prediction model. Let  denote the number of bicycle crashes in the th BSU. Each BSU represents a geographic area, characterised by contextual features. Such contextual features include the characteristics of the areas, such as land use, facility nearby (bridges, parks, etc.) and configuration of cycle tracks (width, pedestrian sidewalks, types of intersection, etc.).  and  refer to the estimated bicycle kilometrage and the th explanatory variables related to contextual characteristics of BSU , respectively. In addition, after adjusting for the exposure and confounders arising from the unstructured and spatially correlated effects, we can identify the factors that have statistically significant effects on the risk of bicycle crashes and quantify their magnitude. These findings should provide invaluable foundations for the upgrade of existing design standards of cycle tracks, thus contributing to a safer bicycle network. For examples, government authorities can define the accident blackspot on cycle tracks that accident frequently occurred, and hence to increase the awareness of cyclists and pedestrians.

  1. The Applicant shall highlight and explain the innovation and technological achievements brought about by the project, the improvements over existing products and technologies, and how such innovation and technological achievements are relevant to the scope of the Fund.

The innovation of this project is threefold:

  1. From an application aspect, bike counts at different locations, bike traffic in a network, and usage of the cycle tracks are typically not known to the Government and relevant authorities. Existing approaches to obtaining the data are mainly based on manual counts and surveys. In this project, bike counts at different locations are recorded continuously and input into an optimization model for inferring bicycle-kilometre (BKM) automatically. The data collected can also be leveraged for novel research in cycling accident and safety research.

  1. From a technological aspect, cameras / sensors are set up at different locations to count and classify objects on cycle tracks for data-driven joint estimation of bike flows in a network. Special objects such as trolleys, e-scooters, electric unicycles will be identified. Multiple technologies (e.g., thermal-imaging cameras and cameras) are deployed for cross-validation and better performance.

  1. From a methodological aspect, a cost-effective flow estimation method which deploys both permanent and mobile thermal imaging cameras for flow estimation is proposed. Novel machine learning, artificial intelligence, and optimization models are developed for bike flow estimation and insight discovery. The methodology may potentially be generalized for other types of vehicles and networks.

  1. Privacy

The Applicant shall identify any potential privacy issues arising from the adoption of the proposed innovations and technological achievements and propose mitigation measures.

Potential privacy concern(s)

Mitigation measure(s)

Images of cyclists, pedestrians, and other bike lane users may be captured.

  • Our solution is to deploy thermal-imaging cameras for object detection and classification such that the exact appearance of the object is not captured. Cameras are for validation and data fusion purposes only.
  • For cameras, the images are processed in an anonymous format such that object is not identifiable.
  • The raw data collected shall be kept for a maximum of 6 months once model training is done.

I/we ⬜ will / ⬛ will not engage an independent party for carrying out a Privacy Impact Assessment on verifying the compliance of prevailing privacy-related laws and regulations.  Subject to the ceiling stipulated in the application guide, I/we understand that the cost will be reimbursed by the Fund.

  1. Please provide information in relation to the expectations on the research output and the business plan where appropriate.

This research project aims to develop a computer vision-based solution to capturing bike flow information on cycling tracks. A pilot study will be conducted in the cycling infrastructure in HKSTP (around 5 km). Upon the successful delivery of the research project, the implementation of the computer vision-based platform can be scaled up to the whole cycling infrastructure in Hong Kong (over 200 km). The R&D outcomes of this project can serve as a technological foundation for extended applications, which include object detection, object classification, and flow estimation on motor vehicle and pedestrian roads. The Transportation Department, other relevant governmental authorities, the community, and business companies that participate in the implementation of the solution will benefit from the development of this innovative technology.

The applications of this innovative technology are not limited to Hong Kong, but also other bicycling-friendly regions around the globe, for example, China, Japan, Germany, Denmark, France, Italy, and the USA. Global tech companies, such as Amazon, Google, IBM, Microsoft, and SIEMENS, which are developing relevant technologies, may be interested in using the IP resulting from this project to deliver similar solutions in their regions.

  1. Please provide information in relation to the future positioning of the deliverables of the Project in the market vis-a-vis existing products and technologies.

We have identified relevant products and technologies developed by companies in the market and in other countries in the world. The most relevant products for smart bike systems are as follows.

  • YUNEX Traffic
    <    https://www.yunextraffic.com/global/en/portfolio/traffic-management/connected-mobility-solutions/intelligent-bike-solutions>
  • Traffic Eye Universal 5
    <    https://www.yunextraffic.com/media/global/traffic-management/pdf/traffic-eye-universal-5-en.pdf >
  • EMTRAC
    <    https://www.emtracsystems.com/traffic/bicycle-and-motorcycle-detection/>
  • ITERIS
    <    https://www.iteris.com/products/pedestrian-and-cyclist/bikeindicator>

Our proposed innovative application distinguishes from the above representative products in the following aspects:

  • Thermal imaging cameras, instead of regular cameras, are deployed to detect and classify objects. Privacy concerns are, therefore, addressed. The use of thermal imaging cameras is also expected to improve the performance of the technology during nighttime and rainy days and under the situation where obstacles block the vision of the camera.
  • The above applications focus on the detection and classification of objects at individual locations and assist in real-time traffic light control. Our proposed framework aggregates bike count information from different locations at different times to estimate the overall bike flow in the network.
  • Our proposed application does not require a large number of thermal imaging cameras to cover the bike flows at all locations; a small number of permanent and mobile thermal imaging cameras will be set up at selected locations to offer a cost-effective solution.

To disseminate the research deliverables, we will work closely together with the Transport Department of the Hong Kong SAR Government. In particular, in the pilot study, we shall seek approval and support of the installation of cameras and other equipment in the pilot area. This pilot study is important to demonstrate the practicality of the proposed technology and showcase the innovative components of the project to the Government and the community. News, industrial conference exhibits / presentations, seminars, reports, and research publications will be prepared to introduce the innovative technology to a broader audience and the industrial parties locally and globally.

The target users will be the governments, municipalities, or relevant authorities in different countries and regions in the world. In Hong Kong, the Hong Kong SAR Government, more specifically, the Transport Department and the Lands Department, will be the primary target users for the technology to understand bike flows for better urban planning, and cycling accident and safety analysis. The secondary users will be bike-sharing operators that may wish to understand the spatial-temporal demands of cyclists. High-tech companies would be potential professional developers that leverage the technologies for systems of a higher industrial standard and a larger-scale implementation.  

The technology can be adopted, further developed, and commercialized by high-tech companies, such as Amazon, Google, IBM, Microsoft, and SIEMENS, for the development and application of smart bike flow estimation solutions.

For market segmentation, the market can be analyzed by the geographic location. The main market will be relevant parties which manage the cycling infrastructure in Hong Kong, where a pilot study will be conducted in HKSTP to demonstrate the practicality of the solution in the local community. The Hong Kong SAR Government, more specifically, the Transport Department and the Lands Department, will be the target users. With a successful case in Hong Kong, the technology will be transferred to other bicycle-friendly cities in the region, e.g., Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, and then to the global market, e.g., Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Netherlands, Spain, and the USA.

Analysis of 4Ps in marketing:

  • Products: While there are existing bike detection solutions in the market (as presented in Section IX.3), our proposed technology is distinguished from these products due to (i) the use of thermal imaging cameras for privacy concerns and higher performance under certain situations where vision is blocked, (ii) bike flow estimation from bike counts at various locations, and (iii) the sampling method which requires substantially fewer thermal imaging cameras to be deployed.
  • Price: Since our method requires only a reduced number of thermal imaging cameras to be set up, a cost-effective solution can be offered.  
  • Place: From the market segmentation analysis, the primary market is in Hong Kong. Upon a successful case in Hong Kong, the technology will be transferred to other bicycle-friendly cities in the region, e.g., Guangzhou, Shenzhen, Zhuhai, and then to the global market, e.g., Belgium, Canada, Denmark, France, Germany, Italy, Japan, Netherlands, Spain, and the USA.
  • Promotion: With the support from the Government (e.g., the Transport Department and Lands Department) and the industrial partners (e.g., Yutraffic Hong Kong and locobike), the technology will be promoted to the industry and community. News, industrial conference exhibits / presentations, seminars, reports, and research publications will be prepared to introduce the innovative technology to a broader audience and the industrial parties locally and globally.
